  <text>
    <body>
      <div>
        <head>1. Introduction</head>
        <p>Intro text. The challenge of extracting structured information from unstructured academic PDFs has motivated a large body of research. In this work, we address the limitations of prior approaches and propose a unified framework.</p>
        <p>More intro. The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section 2 reviews related work. Section 3 describes our method. Section 4 reports experimental results. Section 5 concludes.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <head>2. Method</head>
        <p>Method text. Our method consists of three main components: a layout-aware encoder, a token-level classifier, and a graph-based decoder. Each component is described in detail below.</p>
        <p>We train the model on a corpus of 50,000 annotated academic papers. Training takes approximately 12 hours on 4 NVIDIA A100 GPUs.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <head>3. Results</head>
        <p>Results text. Table 1 summarizes the main results. Our approach outperforms all baselines by a margin of at least 2.3 F1 points, while using 30% fewer parameters than the strongest baseline.</p>
        <p>An ablation study reveals that the layout-aware encoder contributes the largest gain, followed by the graph-based decoder. The token-level classifier contributes the smallest but still meaningful improvement.</p>
      </div>
    </body>
